</div><div class="info-panel__citations info-panel__item"><a href="#tab-citations" class="btn btn--inverse btn--slim" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="View Citations" aria-label="View Citations"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-format_quote"></i></a></div><div class="info-panel__formats info-panel__item"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="Go to purchase options" aria-label="Go to purchase options"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="link-text">Get Access</span></a></div></div></div></div></header><div data-core-nav="header" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-nav-wrapper core-container" aria-label="Article navigation"><div><button aria-controls="article_sections_menu" aria-expanded="false" aria-label="Toggle section navigation menu"><i class="icon-list" aria-hidden="true"></i><span>Contents</span></button><nav id="article_sections_menu" aria-label="Contents" data-core-nav="article"><ul><li><a href="#abstract">Abstract</a></li><li><a href="#core-sec-figures">Figures</a></li><li><a href="#bibliography">References</a></li></ul></nav></div><nav id="article_collateral_menu"><ul class="collateral-pill" data-core-nav="collateral"><li><a href="#core-collateral-info" aria-controls="core-collateral-info" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Information & Authors" title="Information & Authors" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-info"></i><span class="sr-only">Information & Authors</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-metrics" aria-controls="core-collateral-metrics" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Metrics & Citations" title="Metrics & Citations" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-metrics"></i><span class="sr-only">Metrics & Citations</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-controls="core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Get Access" title="Get Access" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="sr-only">Get Access</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-references" aria-controls="core-collateral-references" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="References" title="References" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-references"></i><span class="sr-only">References</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-figures" aria-controls="core-collateral-figures" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Figures" title="Figures" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-photo"></i><span class="sr-only">Figures</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-tables" aria-controls="core-collateral-tables" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Tables" title="Tables" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-table"></i><span class="sr-only">Tables</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-media" aria-controls="core-collateral-media" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Media" title="Media" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-play-circle-filled"></i><span class="sr-only">Media</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-share" aria-controls="core-collateral-share" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Share" title="Share" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-share"></i><span class="sr-only">Share</span></a></li></ul></nav></div></div><div data-core-wrapper="content"><div id="abstracts" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="abstract" property="abstract" typeof="Text" role="doc-abstract"><h2 property="name">Abstract</h2><div role="paragraph">The incidence of ductal carcinoma in situ (DCIS) has increased over the past few decades and now accounts for over 20% of newly diagnosed cases of breast cancer. Although the detection of DCIS has increased with the advent of widespread mammography screening, it is essential to have a more accurate assessment of the extent of DCIS for successful breast conservation therapy. Recent studies evaluating the detection of DCIS with magnetic resonance (MR) imaging have used high spatial resolution techniques and have increasingly been performed to screen a high-risk population as well as to evaluate the extent of disease. This work has shown that MR imaging is the most sensitive modality currently available for identifying DCIS and is more accurate than mammography in evaluating the extent of DCIS. MR imaging is particularly sensitive for identifying high-grade and intermediate-grade DCIS. DCIS may have variable morphologic features on MR images, with non-mass enhancement morphology being the most common manifestation. Less commonly, DCIS may also manifest as a mass on MR images, in which case it is most likely to be irregular. The kinetics of DCIS are also variable, with fast uptake and a plateau curve reported as the most common kinetic pattern. Additional MR imaging tools such as diffusion-weighted imaging and quantitative kinetic analysis combined with the benefit of high field strength, such as 3 T, may increase the sensitivity and specificity of breast MR imaging in the detection of DCIS.</div><div role="paragraph">© RSNA, 2013</div></section></div></div><section id="bodymatter" data-extent="bodymatter" property="articleBody" typeof="Text"><div class="core-container"><section aria-labelledby="denial-block-title" class="denial-block "><h2 id="denial-block-title" class="denial-block__title">Get full access to this article</h2><p class="denial-block__text">View all available purchase options and get full access to this article.</p><div class="denial-block__cta"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span>Get Access</span></a></div><footer class="denial-block__footer"><span>Already a Subscriber? </span><span>Sign in as an </span><a href="/action/showLogin?redirectUri=/doi/10.1148/rg.336125055">individual</a><span> or via your </span><a href="/action/ssostart?uri=/doi/10.1148/rg.336125055">institution</a></footer></section></div></section><section id="backmatter" data-extent="backmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="core-sec-figures" data-type="figures"><h2>Figures</h2><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig01" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336125055/asset/images/large/125055fig01.jpeg" height="1112" width="800" aria-labelledby="fig01" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1</span> High-grade DCIS in a 55-year-old woman who had been recalled after screening mammography. Magnification craniocaudal mammogram demonstrates a 1.2-cm cluster of heterogeneous calcifications (arrow) in the anterior depth of the left breast. Analysis of stereotactic biopsy specimens showed high-grade DCIS of the cribriform and solid types.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336125055&amp;id=fig01">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig02" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336125055/asset/images/large/125055fig02.jpeg" height="577" width="900" aria-labelledby="fig02" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2</span> Low-grade DCIS in a 47-year-old woman with a palpable lump in the left breast. The patient underwent US-guided needle localization of masses (arrows) that had been identified at sonography. Analysis of pathologic specimens yielded low-grade DCIS, separate from invasive ductal carcinoma.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336125055&amp;id=fig02">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig03" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336125055/asset/images/large/125055fig03.jpeg" height="850" width="800" aria-labelledby="fig03" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3</span> High-grade DCIS in a <i>BRCA2</i>-positive 57-year-old woman. Sagittal postcontrast T1-weighted image demonstrates mild background parenchymal enhancement. There is a 2.5-cm area of linear, clumped NME (arrows) in the left breast, 5 cm from the nipple.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336125055&amp;id=fig03">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig04a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336125055/asset/images/large/125055fig04a.jpeg" height="865" width="800" aria-labelledby="fig04a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4a</span> Intermediate-grade DCIS in a 47-year-old woman with a palpable lump in the medial left breast. <b>(a)</b> Sagittal postcontrast T1-weighted image shows a segmental region of clumped NME (arrows) in the inferior left breast, a finding that corresponds to the patient’s palpable lump. <b>(b)</b> Axial postcontrast T1-weighted image shows clumped NME (arrow) in the medial left breast. <b>(c)</b> High-power photomicrograph (original magnification, ×40; hematoxylin-eosin stain) of ductules shows neoplastic cells with marked nuclear pleomorphism (arrow). These findings are compatible with intermediate nuclear grade DCIS.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336125055&amp;id=fig04a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig04b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336125055/asset/images/large/125055fig04b.jpeg" height="734" width="962" aria-labelledby="fig04b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4b</span> Intermediate-grade DCIS in a 47-year-old woman with a palpable lump in the medial left breast. <b>(a)</b> Sagittal postcontrast T1-weighted image shows a segmental region of clumped NME (arrows) in the inferior left breast, a finding that corresponds to the patient’s palpable lump. <b>(b)</b> Axial postcontrast T1-weighted image shows clumped NME (arrow) in the medial left breast. <b>(c)</b> High-power photomicrograph (original magnification, ×40; hematoxylin-eosin stain) of ductules shows neoplastic cells with marked nuclear pleomorphism (arrow). These findings are compatible with intermediate nuclear grade DCIS.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336125055&amp;id=fig04b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig04c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336125055/asset/images/large/125055fig04c.jpeg" height="734" width="912" aria-labelledby="fig04c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4c</span> Intermediate-grade DCIS in a 47-year-old woman with a palpable lump in the medial left breast. <b>(a)</b> Sagittal postcontrast T1-weighted image shows a segmental region of clumped NME (arrows) in the inferior left breast, a finding that corresponds to the patient’s palpable lump. <b>(b)</b> Axial postcontrast T1-weighted image shows clumped NME (arrow) in the medial left breast. <b>(c)</b> High-power photomicrograph (original magnification, ×40; hematoxylin-eosin stain) of ductules shows neoplastic cells with marked nuclear pleomorphism (arrow). These findings are compatible with intermediate nuclear grade DCIS.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336125055&amp;id=fig04c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig05" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336125055/asset/images/large/125055fig05.jpeg" height="865" width="800" aria-labelledby="fig05" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5</span> Intermediate-grade DCIS in a 44-year-old woman with a history of a benign papilloma in the right breast. Sagittal postcontrast subtraction T1-weighted image shows linear, clustered ring NME (arrows) in the central left breast.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336125055&amp;id=fig05">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig06a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336125055/asset/images/large/125055fig06a.jpeg" height="969" width="600" aria-labelledby="fig06a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6a</span> Intermediate-grade DCIS in a 36-year-old woman with a family history of breast cancer and a palpable lump. <b>(a)</b> Magnification craniocaudal mammogram shows regional segmental pleomorphic calcifications (arrows) that underlie the patient’s palpable lump. <b>(b)</b> Sagittal postcontrast T1-weighted image of the breast shows a 7.0 × 3.8 × 2.8-cm area of segmental NME (arrows). The NME involves the nipple anteriorly and extends to within 5 mm of the pectoralis posteriorly. This area demonstrated type 3 (washout) kinetics.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336125055&amp;id=fig06a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig06b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336125055/asset/images/large/125055fig06b.jpeg" height="932" width="809" aria-labelledby="fig06b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6b</span> Intermediate-grade DCIS in a 36-year-old woman with a family history of breast cancer and a palpable lump. <b>(a)</b> Magnification craniocaudal mammogram shows regional segmental pleomorphic calcifications (arrows) that underlie the patient’s palpable lump. <b>(b)</b> Sagittal postcontrast T1-weighted image of the breast shows a 7.0 × 3.8 × 2.8-cm area of segmental NME (arrows). The NME involves the nipple anteriorly and extends to within 5 mm of the pectoralis posteriorly. This area demonstrated type 3 (washout) kinetics.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336125055&amp;id=fig06b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig07" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336125055/asset/images/large/125055fig07.jpeg" height="931" width="766" aria-labelledby="fig07" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7</span> Mixed DCIS involving a radial scar and lobular carcinoma in situ in a 59-year-old woman with a family history of breast cancer. Sagittal postcontrast subtraction image shows a segmental region of clumped NME (arrows) in the right breast.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336125055&amp;id=fig07">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig08a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336125055/asset/images/large/125055fig08a.jpeg" height="830" width="800" aria-labelledby="fig08a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8a</span> Invasive ductal carcinoma and intermediate-grade DCIS in a 36-year-old woman with a palpable lump in the left breast. <b>(a)</b> Magnification mammographic view shows a 9-cm area of regional segmental pleomorphic calcifications (arrows) in the left breast at the 11:00-o'clock position, which correlates with the patient's palpable abnormality. <b>(b)</b> US image shows a 9-cm area of regional segmental pleomorphic calcifications (arrows) in the left breast at the 11:00-o'clock position, a finding that corresponds to the patient's palpable abnormality. <b>(c)</b> Color US image shows a hypoechoic mass with internal vascularity (arrows). This mass corresponds to the patient's palpable lump. <b>(d)</b> Axial postcontrast maximum intensity projection image shows a large region of asymmetric confluent enhancement (arrows) involving the entire medial left breast. This appearance correlates with the patient's mammographic findings. At surgery, a 9-cm region of multifocal DCIS and a 1.4-cm invasive ductal carcinoma (not shown) were found.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336125055&amp;id=fig08a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig08b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336125055/asset/images/large/125055fig08b.jpeg" height="595" width="875" aria-labelledby="fig08b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8b</span> Invasive ductal carcinoma and intermediate-grade DCIS in a 36-year-old woman with a palpable lump in the left breast. <b>(a)</b> Magnification mammographic view shows a 9-cm area of regional segmental pleomorphic calcifications (arrows) in the left breast at the 11:00-o'clock position, which correlates with the patient's palpable abnormality. <b>(b)</b> US image shows a 9-cm area of regional segmental pleomorphic calcifications (arrows) in the left breast at the 11:00-o'clock position, a finding that corresponds to the patient's palpable abnormality. <b>(c)</b> Color US image shows a hypoechoic mass with internal vascularity (arrows). This mass corresponds to the patient's palpable lump. <b>(d)</b> Axial postcontrast maximum intensity projection image shows a large region of asymmetric confluent enhancement (arrows) involving the entire medial left breast. This appearance correlates with the patient's mammographic findings. At surgery, a 9-cm region of multifocal DCIS and a 1.4-cm invasive ductal carcinoma (not shown) were found.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336125055&amp;id=fig08b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig08c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336125055/asset/images/large/125055fig08c.jpeg" height="529" width="964" aria-labelledby="fig08c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8c</span> Invasive ductal carcinoma and intermediate-grade DCIS in a 36-year-old woman with a palpable lump in the left breast. <b>(a)</b> Magnification mammographic view shows a 9-cm area of regional segmental pleomorphic calcifications (arrows) in the left breast at the 11:00-o'clock position, which correlates with the patient's palpable abnormality. <b>(b)</b> US image shows a 9-cm area of regional segmental pleomorphic calcifications (arrows) in the left breast at the 11:00-o'clock position, a finding that corresponds to the patient's palpable abnormality. <b>(c)</b> Color US image shows a hypoechoic mass with internal vascularity (arrows). This mass corresponds to the patient's palpable lump. <b>(d)</b> Axial postcontrast maximum intensity projection image shows a large region of asymmetric confluent enhancement (arrows) involving the entire medial left breast. This appearance correlates with the patient's mammographic findings. At surgery, a 9-cm region of multifocal DCIS and a 1.4-cm invasive ductal carcinoma (not shown) were found.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336125055&amp;id=fig08c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig08d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336125055/asset/images/large/125055fig08d.jpeg" height="529" width="911" aria-labelledby="fig08d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8d</span> Invasive ductal carcinoma and intermediate-grade DCIS in a 36-year-old woman with a palpable lump in the left breast. <b>(a)</b> Magnification mammographic view shows a 9-cm area of regional segmental pleomorphic calcifications (arrows) in the left breast at the 11:00-o'clock position, which correlates with the patient's palpable abnormality. <b>(b)</b> US image shows a 9-cm area of regional segmental pleomorphic calcifications (arrows) in the left breast at the 11:00-o'clock position, a finding that corresponds to the patient's palpable abnormality. <b>(c)</b> Color US image shows a hypoechoic mass with internal vascularity (arrows). This mass corresponds to the patient's palpable lump. <b>(d)</b> Axial postcontrast maximum intensity projection image shows a large region of asymmetric confluent enhancement (arrows) involving the entire medial left breast. This appearance correlates with the patient's mammographic findings. At surgery, a 9-cm region of multifocal DCIS and a 1.4-cm invasive ductal carcinoma (not shown) were found.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336125055&amp;id=fig08d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig09a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336125055/asset/images/large/125055fig09a.jpeg" height="803" width="800" aria-labelledby="fig09a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9a</span> High-grade DCIS in a 45-year-old asymptomatic woman. <b>(a)</b> Magnification craniocaudal mammogram shows an irregular asymmetry, measuring 4.4 × 3.5 × 5.3 cm, with pleomorphic calcifications (arrows) in the middle depth of the right breast. <b>(b)</b> On a US image obtained for further evaluation of the abnormality seen in <b>a</b>, in the region of the mammographic abnormality, there is a 2.4 × 1.8 × 1.3-cm irregular mass (arrow) with associated microcalcifications and posterior acoustic shadowing. <b>(c)</b> Sagittal postcontrast fat-saturated T1-weighted image shows a 7.0 × 4.8 × 6.2-cm irregular enhancing mass (arrow) that correlates with the findings seen in <b>a</b> and <b>b</b>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336125055&amp;id=fig09a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig09b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336125055/asset/images/large/125055fig09b.jpeg" height="735" width="799" aria-labelledby="fig09b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9b</span> High-grade DCIS in a 45-year-old asymptomatic woman. <b>(a)</b> Magnification craniocaudal mammogram shows an irregular asymmetry, measuring 4.4 × 3.5 × 5.3 cm, with pleomorphic calcifications (arrows) in the middle depth of the right breast. <b>(b)</b> On a US image obtained for further evaluation of the abnormality seen in <b>a</b>, in the region of the mammographic abnormality, there is a 2.4 × 1.8 × 1.3-cm irregular mass (arrow) with associated microcalcifications and posterior acoustic shadowing. <b>(c)</b> Sagittal postcontrast fat-saturated T1-weighted image shows a 7.0 × 4.8 × 6.2-cm irregular enhancing mass (arrow) that correlates with the findings seen in <b>a</b> and <b>b</b>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336125055&amp;id=fig09b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig09c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336125055/asset/images/large/125055fig09c.jpeg" height="734" width="776" aria-labelledby="fig09c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9c</span> High-grade DCIS in a 45-year-old asymptomatic woman. <b>(a)</b> Magnification craniocaudal mammogram shows an irregular asymmetry, measuring 4.4 × 3.5 × 5.3 cm, with pleomorphic calcifications (arrows) in the middle depth of the right breast. <b>(b)</b> On a US image obtained for further evaluation of the abnormality seen in <b>a</b>, in the region of the mammographic abnormality, there is a 2.4 × 1.8 × 1.3-cm irregular mass (arrow) with associated microcalcifications and posterior acoustic shadowing. <b>(c)</b> Sagittal postcontrast fat-saturated T1-weighted image shows a 7.0 × 4.8 × 6.2-cm irregular enhancing mass (arrow) that correlates with the findings seen in <b>a</b> and <b>b</b>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336125055&amp;id=fig09c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336125055/asset/images/large/125055fig10.jpeg" height="1826" width="800" aria-labelledby="fig10" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10</span> High-grade DCIS in a 53-year-old woman with a strong family history of breast cancer and multiple prior breast biopsies with benign results. Sagittal postcontrast subtracted image (top) shows a 1.1-cm enhancing lobulated mass (arrow) 4 cm from the nipple. This lesion had been seen at the patient’s prior MR imaging study, but it appeared more prominent at this current examination. There was no T2 hyperintensity. MR imaging–guided biopsy revealed high-grade DCIS. Kinetic analysis (bottom) of the enhancing mass demonstrated persistent kinetics.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336125055&amp;id=fig10">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336125055/asset/images/large/125055fig11a.jpeg" height="774" width="800" aria-labelledby="fig11a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11a</span> Low-grade focal DCIS in a 63-year-old woman with a family history of breast cancer and a history of right lumpectomy and irradiation 14 years prior. <b>(a)</b> Axial postcontrast T1-weighted image demonstrates an 8-mm circumscribed enhancing mass with lobulated margins (arrow) in the left breast at the 2:00-o’clock position. <b>(b)</b> Sagittal postcontrast subtraction image shows the 8-mm enhancing mass (arrow). This lesion demonstrated type 2 (plateau) kinetics and was not visible at US or mammography. MR imaging–guided biopsy revealed low-grade focal DCIS.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336125055&amp;id=fig11a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336125055/asset/images/large/125055fig11b.jpeg" height="815" width="800" aria-labelledby="fig11b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11b</span> Low-grade focal DCIS in a 63-year-old woman with a family history of breast cancer and a history of right lumpectomy and irradiation 14 years prior. <b>(a)</b> Axial postcontrast T1-weighted image demonstrates an 8-mm circumscribed enhancing mass with lobulated margins (arrow) in the left breast at the 2:00-o’clock position. <b>(b)</b> Sagittal postcontrast subtraction image shows the 8-mm enhancing mass (arrow). This lesion demonstrated type 2 (plateau) kinetics and was not visible at US or mammography. MR imaging–guided biopsy revealed low-grade focal DCIS.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336125055&amp;id=fig11b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336125055/asset/images/large/125055fig12.jpeg" height="772" width="800" aria-labelledby="fig12" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12</span> Intermediate-grade DCIS in a 44-year-old woman with negative mammographic findings who underwent screening MR imaging because of a family history of premenopausal breast cancer. Sagittal postcontrast subtraction image shows a 4-mm irregular enhancing focus (arrow) that demonstrated type 3 (washout) kinetics. This lesion was occult at mammography and US, and the patient underwent MR imaging–guided biopsy.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336125055&amp;id=fig12">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336125055/asset/images/large/125055fig13.jpeg" height="842" width="1700" aria-labelledby="fig13" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13</span> High-grade DCIS in a 48-year-old woman with the <i>BRCA1</i> mutation who had been recalled after screening mammography. Sagittal postcontrast subtraction image (left) shows an area of clumped NME measuring up to 2 cm (arrow) in the right breast at the 12:00–1:00-o’clock position. The lesion demonstrated type 2 enhancement kinetics (right). MR imaging–guided biopsy was performed and revealed a high nuclear grade DCIS, solid type with necrosis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336125055&amp;id=fig13">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336125055/asset/images/large/125055fig14.jpeg" height="629" width="1700" aria-labelledby="fig14" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14</span> Low-grade DCIS in a background of atypical ductal hyperplasia in a 52-year-old woman with a history of lobular carcinoma in situ. Sagittal postcontrast subtraction image (left) demonstrates a 1.7-cm area of clumped NME (arrow). The lesion demonstrated persistent (type 1) kinetics (right). Corresponding T2-weighted images (not shown) demonstrated clumped T2 hyperintense foci. MR imaging–guided biopsy of this sonographically occult lesion was performed.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336125055&amp;id=fig14">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336125055/asset/images/large/125055fig15.jpeg" height="846" width="800" aria-labelledby="fig15" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15</span> Intermediate-grade DCIS in a 31-year-old woman with intermittent bloody discharge from the right nipple. Sagittal postcontrast subtraction image shows clumped NME (arrow). The lesion demonstrated washout kinetics. No sonographic correlate was found, so MR imaging–guided biopsy was performed.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336125055&amp;id=fig15">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig16a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336125055/asset/images/large/125055fig16a.jpeg" height="865" width="841" aria-labelledby="fig16a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16a</span> Invasive ductal carcinoma in a background of high-grade DCIS in a 49-year-old woman who had been recalled after screening mammography because of suspicious calcifications. <b>(a)</b> Magnification mediolateral mammogram shows regional heterogeneous calcifications (arrow) in the right breast at the 10:00-o’clock position. The patient underwent stereotactic core biopsy of these calcifications, which were found to be high-grade DCIS and invasive ductal carcinoma, and MR imaging was performed to evaluate the extent of disease. <b>(b)</b> Sagittal postcontrast MR image shows a 1.1-cm irregular enhancing mass in the right breast at the 9:00-o’clock position, posterior depth, consistent with the site of the biopsy-proved malignancy (arrow). The mass is adjacent to the pectoralis muscle, with no evidence of chest wall involvement. An adjacent benign lymph node is seen (arrowhead). <b>(c)</b> High-power photomicrograph (original magnification, unknown; hematoxylin-eosin stain) reveals dilated ducts (arrows) with a proliferation of cells that form secondary lumens (cribriform architecture). Necrosis and calcifications are absent. These findings are compatible with intermediate nuclear grade DCIS.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336125055&amp;id=fig16a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig16b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336125055/asset/images/large/125055fig16b.jpeg" height="865" width="834" aria-labelledby="fig16b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16b</span> Invasive ductal carcinoma in a background of high-grade DCIS in a 49-year-old woman who had been recalled after screening mammography because of suspicious calcifications. <b>(a)</b> Magnification mediolateral mammogram shows regional heterogeneous calcifications (arrow) in the right breast at the 10:00-o’clock position. The patient underwent stereotactic core biopsy of these calcifications, which were found to be high-grade DCIS and invasive ductal carcinoma, and MR imaging was performed to evaluate the extent of disease. <b>(b)</b> Sagittal postcontrast MR image shows a 1.1-cm irregular enhancing mass in the right breast at the 9:00-o’clock position, posterior depth, consistent with the site of the biopsy-proved malignancy (arrow). The mass is adjacent to the pectoralis muscle, with no evidence of chest wall involvement. An adjacent benign lymph node is seen (arrowhead). <b>(c)</b> High-power photomicrograph (original magnification, unknown; hematoxylin-eosin stain) reveals dilated ducts (arrows) with a proliferation of cells that form secondary lumens (cribriform architecture). Necrosis and calcifications are absent. These findings are compatible with intermediate nuclear grade DCIS.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336125055&amp;id=fig16b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig16c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336125055/asset/images/large/125055fig16c.jpeg" height="762" width="901" aria-labelledby="fig16c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16c</span> Invasive ductal carcinoma in a background of high-grade DCIS in a 49-year-old woman who had been recalled after screening mammography because of suspicious calcifications. <b>(a)</b> Magnification mediolateral mammogram shows regional heterogeneous calcifications (arrow) in the right breast at the 10:00-o’clock position. The patient underwent stereotactic core biopsy of these calcifications, which were found to be high-grade DCIS and invasive ductal carcinoma, and MR imaging was performed to evaluate the extent of disease. <b>(b)</b> Sagittal postcontrast MR image shows a 1.1-cm irregular enhancing mass in the right breast at the 9:00-o’clock position, posterior depth, consistent with the site of the biopsy-proved malignancy (arrow). The mass is adjacent to the pectoralis muscle, with no evidence of chest wall involvement. An adjacent benign lymph node is seen (arrowhead). <b>(c)</b> High-power photomicrograph (original magnification, unknown; hematoxylin-eosin stain) reveals dilated ducts (arrows) with a proliferation of cells that form secondary lumens (cribriform architecture). Necrosis and calcifications are absent. These findings are compatible with intermediate nuclear grade DCIS.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336125055&amp;id=fig16c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig17a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336125055/asset/images/large/125055fig17a.jpeg" height="868" width="838" aria-labelledby="fig17a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 17a</span> Multifocal high nuclear grade DCIS in a 41-year-old woman who had been recalled after screening mammography. <b>(a)</b> Magnification mammogram shows a 5-mm cluster of pleomorphic calcifications (arrows) in the anterior depth of the right breast. Stereotactic core biopsy was performed and yielded high-grade DCIS, associated with mucocele-like lesions. <b>(b)</b> Sagittal postcontrast subtraction image demonstrates a 1.5 × 1.1 × 0.9-cm irregular enhancing mass (arrow) in the right breast at the 6:00–7:00-o’clock position. The lesion demonstrated a type 2 kinetics curve and proved to be a second site of DCIS.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336125055&amp;id=fig17a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig17b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336125055/asset/images/large/125055fig17b.jpeg" height="868" width="837" aria-labelledby="fig17b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 17b</span> Multifocal high nuclear grade DCIS in a 41-year-old woman who had been recalled after screening mammography. <b>(a)</b> Magnification mammogram shows a 5-mm cluster of pleomorphic calcifications (arrows) in the anterior depth of the right breast. Stereotactic core biopsy was performed and yielded high-grade DCIS, associated with mucocele-like lesions. <b>(b)</b> Sagittal postcontrast subtraction image demonstrates a 1.5 × 1.1 × 0.9-cm irregular enhancing mass (arrow) in the right breast at the 6:00–7:00-o’clock position. The lesion demonstrated a type 2 kinetics curve and proved to be a second site of DCIS.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336125055&amp;id=fig17b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig18" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336125055/asset/images/large/125055fig18.jpeg" height="858" width="800" aria-labelledby="fig18" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 18</span> High-grade DCIS in a 57-year-old woman who presented with bloody nipple discharge. Sagittal postcontrast subtraction image demonstrates segmental clumped NME (arrows) that extends from the direct subareolar region for approximately 13 cm.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336125055&amp;id=fig18">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig19a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336125055/asset/images/large/125055fig19a.jpeg" height="1187" width="509" aria-labelledby="fig19a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 19a</span> Invasive ductal carcinoma and intermediate-grade DCIS in a 59-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> Magnification mediolateral mammogram shows a 2-cm high-density spiculated mass (arrow). Extensive pleomorphic calcifications (arrowheads) are seen extending from the mass. <b>(b)</b> Sagittal postcontrast T1-weighted image shows a 2.5-cm irregular enhancing mass (arrow) that corresponds to the invasive ductal carcinoma. The region of DCIS does not enhance (arrowhead).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336125055&amp;id=fig19a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig19b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336125055/asset/images/large/125055fig19b.jpeg" height="1187" width="616" aria-labelledby="fig19b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 19b</span> Invasive ductal carcinoma and intermediate-grade DCIS in a 59-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> Magnification mediolateral mammogram shows a 2-cm high-density spiculated mass (arrow). Extensive pleomorphic calcifications (arrowheads) are seen extending from the mass. <b>(b)</b> Sagittal postcontrast T1-weighted image shows a 2.5-cm irregular enhancing mass (arrow) that corresponds to the invasive ductal carcinoma. The region of DCIS does not enhance (arrowhead).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336125055&amp;id=fig19b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig20a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336125055/asset/images/large/125055fig20a.jpeg" height="846" width="611" aria-labelledby="fig20a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 20a</span> Intermediate-grade DCIS in a 29-year-old woman with a strong family history for breast cancer. Results of screening mammography performed 2 weeks prior were normal. <b>(a)</b> Axial postcontrast T1-weighted maximum intensity projection image obtained at 3 T shows segmental clumped enhancement in the lateral left breast. <b>(b)</b> Axial postcontrast T1-weighted image obtained on a 3-T system shows segmental clumped enhancement. MR imaging–guided biopsy revealed multifocal intermediate-grade DCIS.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336125055&amp;id=fig20a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig20b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336125055/asset/images/large/125055fig20b.jpeg" height="846" width="614" aria-labelledby="fig20b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 20b</span> Intermediate-grade DCIS in a 29-year-old woman with a strong family history for breast cancer. Results of screening mammography performed 2 weeks prior were normal. <b>(a)</b> Axial postcontrast T1-weighted maximum intensity projection image obtained at 3 T shows segmental clumped enhancement in the lateral left breast. <b>(b)</b> Axial postcontrast T1-weighted image obtained on a 3-T system shows segmental clumped enhancement. MR imaging–guided biopsy revealed multifocal intermediate-grade DCIS.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336125055&amp;id=fig20b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig21a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336125055/asset/images/large/125055fig21a.jpeg" height="330" width="1899" aria-labelledby="fig21a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 21a</span> Five different cases of breast cancer, examined with postcontrast and DW MR imaging: DCIS <b>(a)</b> and invasive ductal carcinoma <b>(b–e)</b>. Arrowhead = lesion. In each case, from left to right, postcontrast T1-weighted images show lesion location; unweighted (<i>b</i> = 0 sec/mm<sup>2</sup>) DW images show that the lesion is also hyperintense; color ADC maps show lower values in the lesions than in fibroglandular tissue; and in the DW signal intensity profiles from the lesion area and normal tissue, the enlarged scale view highlights the nonexponential response of the lesion tissue (red lines) in comparison with the monoexponential behavior of fibroglandular tissue (black lines). The DCIS lesion in <b>a</b> shows a lower perfusion fraction than most of the invasive ductal carcinoma lesions. (Reprinted, with permission, from reference <a href="#r45" role="doc-biblioref" data-xml-rid="r45">45</a>.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336125055&amp;id=fig21a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig21b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336125055/asset/images/large/125055fig21b.jpeg" height="324" width="1900" aria-labelledby="fig21b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 21b</span> Five different cases of breast cancer, examined with postcontrast and DW MR imaging: DCIS <b>(a)</b> and invasive ductal carcinoma <b>(b–e)</b>. Arrowhead = lesion. In each case, from left to right, postcontrast T1-weighted images show lesion location; unweighted (<i>b</i> = 0 sec/mm<sup>2</sup>) DW images show that the lesion is also hyperintense; color ADC maps show lower values in the lesions than in fibroglandular tissue; and in the DW signal intensity profiles from the lesion area and normal tissue, the enlarged scale view highlights the nonexponential response of the lesion tissue (red lines) in comparison with the monoexponential behavior of fibroglandular tissue (black lines). The DCIS lesion in <b>a</b> shows a lower perfusion fraction than most of the invasive ductal carcinoma lesions. (Reprinted, with permission, from reference <a href="#r45" role="doc-biblioref" data-xml-rid="r45">45</a>.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336125055&amp;id=fig21b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig21c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336125055/asset/images/large/125055fig21c.jpeg" height="338" width="1900" aria-labelledby="fig21c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 21c</span> Five different cases of breast cancer, examined with postcontrast and DW MR imaging: DCIS <b>(a)</b> and invasive ductal carcinoma <b>(b–e)</b>. Arrowhead = lesion. In each case, from left to right, postcontrast T1-weighted images show lesion location; unweighted (<i>b</i> = 0 sec/mm<sup>2</sup>) DW images show that the lesion is also hyperintense; color ADC maps show lower values in the lesions than in fibroglandular tissue; and in the DW signal intensity profiles from the lesion area and normal tissue, the enlarged scale view highlights the nonexponential response of the lesion tissue (red lines) in comparison with the monoexponential behavior of fibroglandular tissue (black lines). The DCIS lesion in <b>a</b> shows a lower perfusion fraction than most of the invasive ductal carcinoma lesions. (Reprinted, with permission, from reference <a href="#r45" role="doc-biblioref" data-xml-rid="r45">45</a>.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336125055&amp;id=fig21c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig21d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336125055/asset/images/large/125055fig21d.jpeg" height="323" width="1900" aria-labelledby="fig21d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 21d</span> Five different cases of breast cancer, examined with postcontrast and DW MR imaging: DCIS <b>(a)</b> and invasive ductal carcinoma <b>(b–e)</b>. Arrowhead = lesion. In each case, from left to right, postcontrast T1-weighted images show lesion location; unweighted (<i>b</i> = 0 sec/mm<sup>2</sup>) DW images show that the lesion is also hyperintense; color ADC maps show lower values in the lesions than in fibroglandular tissue; and in the DW signal intensity profiles from the lesion area and normal tissue, the enlarged scale view highlights the nonexponential response of the lesion tissue (red lines) in comparison with the monoexponential behavior of fibroglandular tissue (black lines). The DCIS lesion in <b>a</b> shows a lower perfusion fraction than most of the invasive ductal carcinoma lesions. (Reprinted, with permission, from reference <a href="#r45" role="doc-biblioref" data-xml-rid="r45">45</a>.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336125055&amp;id=fig21d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig21e" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336125055/asset/images/large/125055fig21e.jpeg" height="384" width="1900" aria-labelledby="fig21e" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 21e</span> Five different cases of breast cancer, examined with postcontrast and DW MR imaging: DCIS <b>(a)</b> and invasive ductal carcinoma <b>(b–e)</b>. Arrowhead = lesion. In each case, from left to right, postcontrast T1-weighted images show lesion location; unweighted (<i>b</i> = 0 sec/mm<sup>2</sup>) DW images show that the lesion is also hyperintense; color ADC maps show lower values in the lesions than in fibroglandular tissue; and in the DW signal intensity profiles from the lesion area and normal tissue, the enlarged scale view highlights the nonexponential response of the lesion tissue (red lines) in comparison with the monoexponential behavior of fibroglandular tissue (black lines). The DCIS lesion in <b>a</b> shows a lower perfusion fraction than most of the invasive ductal carcinoma lesions. (Reprinted, with permission, from reference <a href="#r45" role="doc-biblioref" data-xml-rid="r45">45</a>.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336125055&amp;id=fig21e">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig22a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336125055/asset/images/large/125055fig22a.jpeg" height="442" width="876" aria-labelledby="fig22a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 22a</span> Diagrams illustrate diffusion tensor imaging <b>(a)</b> and intravoxel incoherent motion tissue and analysis <b>(b)</b>. Diffusion tensor imaging measures diffusion anisotropy from ordered microstructure, whereas intravoxel incoherent motion separates microscopic incoherent flow and diffusion. <i>b</i> = diffusion weighting factor, <i>D</i><sub><i>p</i></sub> = pseudodiffusivity, <i>D</i><sub><i>t</i></sub> = tissue diffusivity, <i>f</i><sub><i>p</i></sub> = perfusion fraction, <i>M</i> = magnetization, λ<sub>1</sub> = principal diffusion eigenvalue, λ<sub>2</sub> = secondary diffusion eigenvalue, λ<sub>3</sub> = tertiary diffusion eigenvalue. (Reprinted, with permission, from reference <a href="#r48" role="doc-biblioref" data-xml-rid="r48">48</a>.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336125055&amp;id=fig22a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig22b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336125055/asset/images/large/125055fig22b.jpeg" height="451" width="999" aria-labelledby="fig22b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 22b</span> Diagrams illustrate diffusion tensor imaging <b>(a)</b> and intravoxel incoherent motion tissue and analysis <b>(b)</b>. Diffusion tensor imaging measures diffusion anisotropy from ordered microstructure, whereas intravoxel incoherent motion separates microscopic incoherent flow and diffusion. <i>b</i> = diffusion weighting factor, <i>D</i><sub><i>p</i></sub> = pseudodiffusivity, <i>D</i><sub><i>t</i></sub> = tissue diffusivity, <i>f</i><sub><i>p</i></sub> = perfusion fraction, <i>M</i> = magnetization, λ<sub>1</sub> = principal diffusion eigenvalue, λ<sub>2</sub> = secondary diffusion eigenvalue, λ<sub>3</sub> = tertiary diffusion eigenvalue. (Reprinted, with permission, from reference <a href="#r48" role="doc-biblioref" data-xml-rid="r48">48</a>.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336125055&amp;id=fig22b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div></section><section id="bibliography" role="doc-bibliography"><h2>References</h2><div role="list"><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">1.</div><div id="r1" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Mossa-Basha M, Fundaro GM, Shah BA, Ali S, Pantelic MV. Ductal carcinoma in situ of the breast: MR imaging findings with histopathologic correlation. <em>RadioGraphics</em> 2010;30(6):1673–1687.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-crossref"><a href="https://doi.org/10.1148/rg.306105510">Crossref</a></div><div class="core-xlink-pubmed"><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/21071382/">PubMed</a></div><div class="core-xlink-google-scholar"><a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar_lookup?title=Ductal+carcinoma+in+situ+of+the+breast%3A+MR+imaging+findings+with+histopathologic+correlation&amp;author=M+Mossa-Basha&amp;author=GM+Fundaro&amp;author=BA+Shah&amp;author=S+Ali&amp;author=MV+Pantelic&amp;publication_year=2010&amp;journal=RadioGraphics&amp;pages=1673-1687&amp;doi=10.1148%2Frg.306105510&amp;pmid=21071382">Google Scholar</a></div></div></div></div></div><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">2.</div><div id="r2" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Ozzello L. Ultrastructure of intra-epithelial carcinomas of the breast. <em>Cancer</em> 1971;28(6):1508–1515.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-crossref"><a href="https://doi.org/10.1002/1097-0142(197112)28:6%3C1508::AID-CNCR2820280625%3E3.0.CO;2-K">Crossref</a></div><div class="core-xlink-pubmed"><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/4108411/">PubMed</a></div><div class="core-xlink-google-scholar"><a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar_lookup?title=Ultrastructure+of+intra-epithelial+carcinomas+of+the+breast&amp;author=L+Ozzello&amp;publication_year=1971&amp;journal=Cancer&amp;pages=1508-1515&amp;doi=10.1002%2F1097-0142%28197112%2928%3A6%253C1508%3A%3AAID-CNCR2820280625%253E3.0.CO%3B2-K&amp;pmid=4108411">Google Scholar</a></div></div></div></div></div><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">3.</div><div id="r3" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Recht A, Rutgers EJ, Fentiman IS, Kurtz JM, Mansel RE, Sloane JP. The fourth EORTC DCIS Consensus meeting (Château Marquette, Heemskerk, The Netherlands, 23-24 January 1998)—conference report. <em>Eur J Cancer</em> 1998;34(11):1664–1669.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-crossref"><a href="https://doi.org/10.1016/S0959-8049(98)00220-2">Crossref</a></div><div class="core-xlink-pubmed"><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/9893649/">PubMed</a></div><div class="core-xlink-google-scholar"><a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar_lookup?ti